Another question involving a multitude of details is the use of ie or es in the accus. plur. of participles and adjectives and substantivas whose gen. plur. ends in iam, as well as of some other classes, doloris or dolores, alcioris or araiores: here too Wagner involves himself in inex· tricable perplexities by his eclectic system, when his mss were admirable guidae, had he chosen to follow them. The mss, oi Lucretius are no less admirable and probably represent very fairly the author's own usage :⁴ they offer -is five times out of six; and es is somewhat more common in substantivas in very general use, as ipues vires aures.
